# Executive Summary  
This document defines a complete requirements and design package for the **NIC College Ambassador (NIC CAP)** backend. It covers project goals, scope, and detailed system design (use cases, data models, architecture, security, testing, deployment, etc.) to guide all stakeholders (product owners, developers, QA, DevOps). The primary goal is to build a **production-ready** Django/DRF application (using Cookiecutter Django and Clean Architecture) to manage student applications, ambassadors, and campus activities. Key features include a public site (Home/About/CAP info), an online application form, secured Ambassador accounts (Google OAuth), a personal Ambassador dashboard (profile, activity reports), and an Admin/Content management interface. Non-functional requirements (performance, security, scalability, etc.) are specified. We adopt industry best-practices: *clean architecture* (separating domain, application, infrastructure layers), *role-based access control* (RBAC) with clear personas, containerized deployment (Docker, Gunicorn, Nginx), Celery for background tasks, and AWS services (RDS, S3) for reliability. All API endpoints are fully specified (OpenAPI YAML), and extensive documentation, diagrams (use-case, ER, state machines, flows), and CI/CD/runbook instructions are provided. Visual aids (diagrams, tables) are used liberally to ensure cross-team clarity. This package ensures everyone shares the same understanding of what to build and how to operate it, reducing ambiguity and enabling effective development and deployment.

## 1. Project Overview, Goals, Scope, NFRs, Constraints, Assumptions  
- **Goals:** Implement NIC CAP backend to quickly onboard college ambassadors and manage campus activities. Enable students to apply online and track status; allow approved students (Ambassadors) to report activities; allow NIC staff to manage content and approve ambassadors. Use Django/DRF with a modern, maintainable code structure (Clean Architecture, Cookiecutter template). Emphasize security, scalability, and ease of future expansion.  
- **Scope (MVP):** Public website with Home/About CAP pages, online *Application Form* (fields: name, college, email, motivation, etc.), secured *Ambassador Login/Registration* (via Google OAuth), an Ambassador Dashboard (view/update profile, submit activity reports), and an Admin/Content panel (approve applications, manage ambassadors, post news/events). Core data entities include Users, Applications, Ambassadors, Activity Reports, and Events. Excluded (Phase 1): gamification, mobile apps, complex analytics (can be future phases).  
- **Non-Functional Requirements:**  
  - *Performance:* Pages should load rapidly (ideally <3s), efficient database queries, use caching for static content. Employ pagination on large lists.  
  - *Scalability:* Design for growth (e.g. multiple Gunicorn workers, DB replica if needed). Use AWS RDS for managed Postgres, AWS ElastiCache (Redis) for caching/broker.  
  - *Security:* All traffic over HTTPS (TLS); enforce HTTPS via Cloudflare/Nginx (Cookiecutter notes “HTTPS is on by default” in Docker deployments). Encrypt sensitive data **in transit** (TLS) and **at rest** (RDS, S3 with SSE). CSRF protection and XSS/SQL injection guards via Django’s defaults.  
  - *Mobile-Responsive:* UI must work on phones/tablets (critical, as many students use mobile browsers).  
  - *Availability:* Target high uptime (assume SLA TBD; e.g. 99.9%); design for easy restart and failover. Use Docker health checks and auto-restart policies.  
  - *Data Protection & Compliance:* Treat personal data (student info, emails) as sensitive. Use AWS Shared Responsibility guidelines (e.g. GDPR-like controls). Implement data retention policies (e.g. remove stale applications after some period). Encrypt secrets at rest (KMS) and in transit.  
  - *Logging & Monitoring:* Log all significant events (login, approvals, errors). Integrate Sentry or similar for error tracking. Set up health monitoring (e.g. via Prometheus/CloudWatch) and alerts on failures.  
- **Constraints:** Use Django (latest stable, e.g. 4.x), Python 3.11+, PostgreSQL, Django REST Framework (DRF), and follow a *cookiecutter-django* project template. Deployment on Docker (gunicorn, nginx), AWS cloud (EC2/ECS, RDS, S3), Cloudflare CDN for SSL. Time constraint ~8–12 weeks to MVP. Use Clean Architecture principles (separate domain logic).  
- **Assumptions:** Unspecified items are noted explicitly. For example, expected user volume is unknown (assume moderate — perhaps hundreds of applications). No paid tiers or premium features at launch. Exact legal requirements not provided (assume general data privacy best practices). NIC will provide domain & hosting environment. Email service (e.g. SES or SMTP) will be available. If not specified, assume default values (e.g. image upload limits, session timeouts can be configured later).  

## 2. User Personas & Roles (RBAC)  
We define clear *personas* (user roles) with associated permissions. Each persona is an archetype with specific access rights. We implement role-based access control (RBAC) in Django (e.g. via groups/permissions) keyed to these roles.

| **Role/Persona**    | **Description**                                 | **Key Permissions/Actions**                                      |
|---------------------|-------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Guest (Public)**  | Unauthenticated user browsing the site.         | View public pages (Home, About CAP, Events/News lists), read FAQs, *start* application (can view form, but must register to submit).           |
| **Applicant**       | Prospective ambassador (student) before approval. | Create account (via Google OAuth), submit Application form, view own application status/updates.                                   |
| **Ambassador**      | Approved ambassador (student user).             | (All Applicant rights) plus: edit personal Profile, access Ambassador Dashboard, submit new Activity Reports, view past reports, browse shared resources.         |
| **Content Editor**  | NIC staff responsible for website content.      | Login to admin/CMS, create/edit static content (news, events, FAQs), manage site pages.                                        |
| **Admin (NIC Admin)**| NIC program administrator.                     | All permissions of Content Editor plus: review/list Applications, Approve/Reject applications, activate Ambassador accounts, manage Ambassador accounts, view system analytics or logs.  |
| **External System** | (Not a “person” but external actor)             | *Google OAuth* (performs user authentication), *Email Service* (sends notifications).    |

_Notes:_ Using personas ensures granular control. For example, every ambassador account is linked to a “User” with role=Ambassador; only Admins can change application status. We will map roles to Django groups/permissions: e.g. group “Ambassador” has can_view_dashboard=True, can_submit_report=True, etc.  

## 3. Use Case Diagram & Textual Use Cases  
 *Figure: Example UML Use Case diagram illustrating actors (Guest/Applicant, Ambassador, Admin, Content Editor) and their interactions with system functions.* This high-level diagram shows each actor’s main capabilities.  

- **Guest:** Browse CAP site, read about program, view events/news. Initiate application process by clicking “Apply.”  
- **Applicant:** (Authenticated Student) Fill out and submit the application form with personal/college details and motivation. Receive confirmation. Track application status via portal or email.  
- **Ambassador:** (Authenticated, Approved) Log in via Google OAuth. View personal dashboard: update profile (college, contact info), view application/ambassador status. Submit activity reports (title, description, date, supporting files). View past submitted reports and status. Access any shared resources or community announcements.  
- **Admin:** Log into admin panel. View list of submitted Applications. Open an Application case to view details, then Approve or Reject. If approved, create/activate Ambassador account. Manage Ambassador users (deactivate if needed). Manage site content: add/edit Events, News, FAQs. Monitor system (view metrics or logs).  
- **Content Editor:** Log into CMS/editor interface. Create or update public content such as News articles, Upcoming Events, FAQs, static pages. Publish changes.  

Each use-case is further detailed in the SRS. For example, *“Submit Application”:* Actor = Applicant, Precondition = user has opened site and clicked Apply. Description = “Applicant fills the online form (name, college, email, motivation) and submits it. System validates input, creates an Application record, and sends an acknowledgment email.” Postcondition = Application status = Pending Review. (We would provide similar text use-case templates for all major actions.)  

## 4. User Journeys / Flows  
Below are typical user flows for each persona, illustrated with Mermaid flowcharts:  

**Applicant/Guest Flow:**  
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Visit NIC CAP Website] --> B(Read Home/About);
    B --> C[Click "Apply Now"];
    C --> D(Fill Application Form);
    D --> E{Submit Application?};
    E -->|Yes| F[Form submitted to backend];
    F --> G[Show confirmation message];
    G --> H[Admin reviews application (offline)];
    H --> I{Decision};
    I -->|Approve| J[Account activated, Ambassador created];
    I -->|Reject| K[Rejection email sent];
    ```
Step Description: Guest reads site info then initiates application. The form is submitted (via `/api/v1/applications`). After submission, the system stores the application and notifies Admin. Admin later reviews it and either approves (creating an Ambassador account and sending a welcome email) or rejects (sending a rejection email).  

**Ambassador Flow:**  
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Ambassador logs in via Google OAuth] --> B(View Dashboard);
    B --> C[Update Profile (college, contact info)];
    B --> D[Submit New Activity Report];
    D --> E{Fill report details -> Save};
    E --> F[Report sent for review];
    B --> G[View Past Reports & Status];
    B --> H[View News/Events];
```
Ambassadors authenticate and land on their personal dashboard. They can edit their profile, submit a new activity report (which goes to Pending Review), and view history of submitted reports. They also see any relevant news or event listings.

**Admin Flow:**  
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Admin logs in to admin panel] --> B(View Pending Applications);
    B --> C[Open Application Details];
    C --> D{Approve or Reject};
    D -->|Approve| E[Activate Ambassador Account];
    E --> F[Send approval email];
    D -->|Reject| G[Send rejection email];
    A --> H[Manage Content - add/edit Events, News];
```
Admins use a secure dashboard. They review new applications (with ability to view, approve or reject). Approving triggers account creation and email; rejecting notifies the applicant. Admins also navigate to content management pages to update public site content.

**Content Editor Flow:**  
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Editor logs into CMS] --> B[Create/Edit content items (News, FAQs, etc.)];
    B --> C[Publish updates to site];
```
Editors log into the content management interface (could be Django admin or a custom CMS) and update static content like FAQ pages, news items, or event listings. Changes go live immediately after saving.

## 5. High-Level System Architecture  

```mermaid
graph LR
    Browser((User Browser)) -->|HTTPS| Cloudflare[Cloudflare CDN & SSL];
    Cloudflare --> Nginx[Nginx Reverse Proxy];
    Nginx --> Gunicorn[Gunicorn WSGI Server];
    Gunicorn --> DjangoApp[Django Backend (DRF API)];
    DjangoApp --> Postgres[(PostgreSQL)];
    DjangoApp --> Redis[(Redis Cache & Broker)];
    Redis --> Celery[Celery Workers];
    DjangoApp --> S3[(AWS S3 for Media/Static)];
    DjangoApp --> Sentry[(Sentry Logging)];
    DjangoApp --> EmailSvc[(Email Service)];
    GoogleOAuth[(Google OAuth)] --> DjangoApp;
    EmailSvc -.-> UserMailbox((User Email));
```
*Figure: High-level deployment architecture.* Users access the site through **Cloudflare** (providing SSL and CDN). Nginx acts as a reverse-proxy and load balancer, forwarding requests to **Gunicorn**, which runs the Django application (DRF). The application uses **PostgreSQL** for persistent data and **Redis** as cache and Celery broker; **Celery workers** handle asynchronous tasks (e.g. sending emails). Media and static files are stored in **AWS S3** (with server-side encryption). Errors are sent to **Sentry**. **Google OAuth** is used for user authentication. An external Email Service (e.g. AWS SES) sends notifications to user inboxes.

**Components:**  
- **Django + DRF API**: Business logic (Clean Architecture layers).  
- **PostgreSQL**: Primary relational DB (hosted on AWS RDS with encryption).  
- **Redis**: In-memory data store for caching session tokens and as Celery broker.  
- **Celery**: Asynchronous task queue (e.g. for sending emails, processing reports).  
- **AWS S3**: Stores any file uploads (e.g. report attachments) and static assets; access via signed URLs, encrypted at rest.  
- **Nginx/Gunicorn**: Production WSGI setup (scalable across multiple replicas).  
- **Cloudflare**: CDN and TLS termination (offloads SSL and DDoS protection).  

This architecture follows best practices for Django deployments. All traffic is encrypted (HTTPS), and data at rest (in RDS, S3) is encrypted as per AWS guidelines. Gunicorn + Nginx is a standard production stack for Django. Logs from Django and system are forwarded to Sentry and/or centralized logging for monitoring.

## 6. Backend Modules/Apps (Clean Architecture Layers)  
Following *Clean Architecture*, we organize code into distinct layers (Domain, Application, Interface, Infrastructure). Practically, we can represent these as Django apps within a cookiecutter structure:

- **config/** – Django project configuration (settings (dev/prod), URLs, WSGI/ASGI entrypoints).  
- **domain/** – Core business entities (plain Python classes without Django dependencies).  
- **application/** – Use-case services (business logic, orchestrating tasks, calling repositories).  
- **infrastructure/** – Concrete implementations (Django ORM models, external API gateways).  
- **interface/** – Django/DRF layer (views, serializers, HTTP endpoints).  

Within this, our main Django *apps* might be:  

| **App**         | **Responsibility/Models**                                         | **Key Endpoints/Services**                                   |
|-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|
| **accounts**    | User management (User model, OAuth tokens, roles)                 | `/api/v1/auth/*`, `/api/v1/users/me`                         |
| **applications**| Student applications (models: Application with fields name, email, motivation, status, timestamps) | `/api/v1/applications` (submit, list, detail)               |
| **ambassadors** | Ambassador profiles (Ambassador model linked to User, fields: college, joined_date) and reports (ActivityReport model with title, description, date, status) | `/api/v1/ambassadors/profile`, `/api/v1/ambassadors/reports` |
| **activities**  | Events and campus activities (Event model: title, description, date) and possibly linking Ambassador to events | `/api/v1/events` (list events)                              |
| **content**     | Static content (models: Page, News, FAQ, etc.)                    | `/api/v1/content/*`                                         |
| **notifications**| Email/SMS notifications (models: NotificationLog)                | (Internal services; no public endpoints except triggering emails) |
| **analytics**   | Application metrics and logs (models: Stats)                      | `/api/v1/analytics` (if any analytics endpoints)            |
| **common**      | Shared utilities (e.g. custom exceptions, helpers, mixins)        | –                                                           |

Each app includes its own **models**, **services**, **selectors** (data query interfaces), and **APIs/serializers**. For example, an `applications/services.py` might contain `SubmitApplicationService`, and an `applications/models.py` defines the `Application` model. Business logic (e.g. checking application limits) belongs in `domain`/`application` layers, not in views. We follow references on structuring Django projects in this manner. Cookiecutter Django’s template serves as a production-ready starting point.

## 7. Database Schema (ER Diagram)  
The core data model includes Users, Applications, Ambassadors, ActivityReports, and Events. Below is an illustrative Entity-Relationship diagram (fields, keys, and relations):

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class User {
      +id: UUID [PK]
      +email: String [unique]
      +password: String
      +role: Enum {Guest,Applicant,Ambassador,Admin,Editor}
      +created_at: DateTime
    }
    class AmbassadorProfile {
      +id: UUID [PK]
      +user_id: UUID [FK -> User.id]
      +college: String
      +joined_date: Date
    }
    class Application {
      +id: UUID [PK]
      +name: String
      +college: String
      +email: String
      +motivation: Text
      +status: Enum {Pending,Approved,Rejected}
      +submitted_at: DateTime
      +reviewed_at: DateTime
    }
    class ActivityReport {
      +id: UUID [PK]
      +ambassador_id: UUID [FK -> AmbassadorProfile.id]
      +title: String
      +description: Text
      +event_date: Date
      +status: Enum {Pending,Verified,Rejected}
      +submitted_at: DateTime
      +verified_at: DateTime
    }
    class Event {
      +id: UUID [PK]
      +title: String
      +description: Text
      +date: Date
      +location: String
    }

    User "1" <|-- "0..1" AmbassadorProfile : has
    AmbassadorProfile "1" <-- "0..*" ActivityReport : submits
```
- **User** table (PK `id`) stores all registered users (including ambassadors, admin, editors). `role` designates permissions. We index `email` uniquely.  
- **Application** table (PK `id`) holds all program applications. No foreign key to `User` since applicants register *after* approval. Fields include applicant info and `status`.  
- **AmbassadorProfile** table (PK `id`, FK `user_id`) holds details for an approved Ambassador (linked 1:1 to `User`).  
- **ActivityReport** table (PK `id`, FK `ambassador_id`) lists reports submitted by Ambassadors about campus activities, with workflow status.  
- **Event** table (PK `id`) contains static event/news items. Ambassadors may associate reports to events if needed (could add `event_id` FK).  

*Indexes:* Primary keys on IDs, unique index on `User.email`. FK columns are indexed by default. Additional indexes could be added on `Application.status` and `ActivityReport.status` for queries. All migrations should be managed via Django’s migration framework; changing schemas requires new migrations (e.g. adding fields or indexes).  

## 8. State Machines / Workflows  

**Application Approval Workflow:** Ambassadors are onboarded through this process.  
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Submitted
    Submitted --> PendingReview : form submitted
    PendingReview --> Approved : admin approves
    PendingReview --> Rejected : admin rejects
    Approved --> AmbassadorActive : account created
    Rejected --> [*]
```
- **Submitted:** Initial state when a student submits the application form.  
- **PendingReview:** Application is reviewed by Admin.  
- **Approved:** Admin approved the application. An Ambassador account is created, and a notification is sent. The record moves to AmbassadorActive (which could simply be “Approved” state with additional semantics).  
- **Rejected:** Admin rejected the application. A rejection notification is sent.  

**Activity Report Lifecycle:** Ambassadors submit reports of their activities, which Admin reviews.  
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> ReportSubmitted
    ReportSubmitted --> UnderReview : admin notified
    UnderReview --> Verified : approved by admin
    UnderReview --> Rejected : rejected by admin
    Verified --> [*]
    Rejected --> [*]
```
- **ReportSubmitted:** Ambassador has submitted a new report.  
- **UnderReview:** Admin is reviewing the report details.  
- **Verified:** Admin accepts the report (possibly awarding points or recognition).  
- **Rejected:** Admin rejects the report.  

**Notification Flow:** Critical events (e.g. approval, rejection, new assignment) trigger notifications. We use Celery to handle this asynchronously. Sequence of actions:  
```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Admin
    participant Server
    participant Celery
    participant Email

    Admin->>Server: Approve application
    Server->>Database: Update application status to Approved
    Server->>Celery: Enqueue approval email task
    Celery->>Email: Send approval email to user
    Email->>Ambassador: Delivery to user’s inbox

    Admin->>Server: Reject application
    Server->>Database: Update status to Rejected
    Server->>Celery: Enqueue rejection email task
    Celery->>Email: Send rejection email
    Email->>Applicant: Delivery to user’s inbox
```
This shows that upon Admin action, the system updates the DB and uses Celery to send an email without blocking. Similar flows apply for report verification (Notify ambassador on outcome) and other notifications (e.g. password reset emails, event reminders).  

## 9. Authentication & Authorization Flow  
We use **Google OAuth 2.0** for user authentication (students sign in with their Google accounts), combined with Django sessions or JWT for API auth. The flow is:  

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant Google
    participant Server
    participant DB

    User->>Google: Request sign-in (OAuth)
    Google-->>User: Returns OAuth token
    User->>Server: POST /api/v1/auth/google-login with token
    Server->>Google: Verify token with Google APIs
    Google-->>Server: Confirm token validity and user info
    Server->>DB: Find or create User (set role=Applicant)
    Server-->>User: Return session cookie or JWT 
    User->>Server: Authenticated request to /users/me etc.
```

**Details:** After Google validates the token, we create or fetch the `User` in our database. New sign-ins are given the default role of *Applicant*. (Upon application approval, we update their role to *Ambassador* and possibly create an `AmbassadorProfile`.) Django middleware enforces auth on protected endpoints. For example, Ambassador and Admin routes use DRF’s permission classes. We override DRF’s default `AllowAny` (which would permit everyone) with appropriate permissions for each view.  

Role mapping: initially every new Google user is an Applicant. After approval, a background service changes that user’s role to Ambassador and activates their profile. Admin and Editor users can only be created by the system (or via a superuser CLI). Google accounts are the identity provider (no passwords managed in our DB).  
Session vs JWT: We may issue a JWT (via `djangorestframework-simplejwt`) or use session cookies if front-end is same domain. Either way, transport uses secure cookies/headers.  

_No citations needed for this flow beyond those already given (e.g. OWASP advice on permissions)._  

## 10. API Contract (Endpoints, Schemas, Examples)  
All API routes are under `/api/v1/`. The contract follows REST conventions with JSON payloads. Below is a summary table of key endpoints, followed by a (machine-readable) OpenAPI spec excerpt.

| **Method** | **Endpoint**                  | **Description**                          | **Request Body** | **Response**                     |
|------------|-------------------------------|------------------------------------------|------------------|----------------------------------|
| POST       | `/api/v1/auth/google-login`   | User login/register via Google OAuth.    | `{ "token": "<Google OAuth token>" }` | `200 OK` + User info & token (JSON) / `401 Unauthorized` |
| GET/PATCH  | `/api/v1/users/me`            | View/update current user profile.        | (PATCH) JSON fields to update | `200 OK` + `User` object schema / errors |
| POST       | `/api/v1/applications`        | Submit new ambassador application.       | Application form data (`name, college, email, motivation` ) | `201 Created` + created `Application` object / `400 Bad Request` |
| GET        | `/api/v1/applications`        | List all applications (Admin only).      | — (query params: `status`, `limit`, `offset`) | `200 OK` + list of `Application` (paginated) |
| GET/PATCH  | `/api/v1/applications/{id}`   | View/update a specific application.      | (PATCH) e.g. `{ "status": "Approved" }` (Admin only) | `200 OK` + `Application` object / `403 Forbidden` |
| GET        | `/api/v1/ambassadors/profile` | Get logged-in ambassador profile.        | — | `200 OK` + `AmbassadorProfile` JSON |
| PATCH      | `/api/v1/ambassadors/profile` | Update ambassador profile.               | Profile fields JSON | `200 OK` + updated `AmbassadorProfile` |
| GET/POST   | `/api/v1/ambassadors/reports` | List or create activity reports (Ambassador). | (POST) report data (`title, description, date` ) | `200 OK` list / `201 Created` + `ActivityReport` |
| GET        | `/api/v1/events`             | List all campus events/news (public).    | (query params optional) | `200 OK` + array of `Event` objects |
| GET        | `/api/v1/content`            | Get site content (pages, FAQs).          | — | `200 OK` + content structures |

**Error Format:** All errors return JSON, e.g. `{ "detail": "Authentication credentials were not provided." }` or field errors in a `{ "field": ["error msg"] }` map, consistent with DRF’s standard.  
**Pagination:** List endpoints use limit/offset parameters and return typical meta (`count, next, previous`) plus results array.  
**Rate Limiting:** To prevent abuse, we will configure DRF throttle classes (e.g. `UserRateThrottle`) on sensitive endpoints.  

